SIMPLE: inhibition
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inhibition
<hw>In`hi*bi"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>inhibitio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>inhibition</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of inhibiting, or the state of being
inhibited; restraint; prohibition; embargo.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>A stopping or checking of an
already present action; a restraining of the function of an organ, or an
agent, as a digestive fluid or enzyme, etc.; <as>as, the
<ex>inhibition</ex> of the respiratory center by the pneumogastric
nerve; the <ex>inhibition</ex> of reflexes, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A writ from a higher court
forbidding an inferior judge from further proceedings in a cause before;
esp., a writ issuing from a higher ecclesiastical court to an inferior
one, on appeal.</def> <rj><au>Cowell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Chem., Biochem.)</fld> <def>The reduction in rate
or stopping of a chemical or biochemical reaction, due to interaction
with a chemical agent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inhibitor</ent>⟦br⟧
